Good morning everyone and happy Monday!

As we go into this week, we would like to appreciate all of the teachers that are working so hard to make this school year possible! If you are a teacher, or part of our school’s administration, thank you so much! What you have done thus far has not been easy. To show you our appreciation here at Sweet Annie’s, we would love to give you 10% off of ALL your orders from today, 8/24 through Saturday 8/29!

Please tag teachers/administrators in our post to let them know they are appreciated! Have a great day!

post_text:
STATEMENT #2 FROM PAMLICO COUNTY SCHOOLS REGARDING COVID-19

Pamlico County Schools, March 14, 2020 – Please note that this information is accurate as of March 14, 2020 – 4:30 P.M. We are continuing to monitor this evolving situation, and we will provide updates.
Pamlico County Schools continues to closely monitor state and local health information on COVID-19.
At 4:30 today, North Carolina Governor Roy Cooper ordered all public schools to be closed to students beginning Monday, March 16, 2020. Monday, March 16 will be a teacher workday to allow staff and students to access the schools to retrieve personal items and resources. This closure will be for at least 2 weeks, March 16 – March 30
Please continue to monitor local media, school websites, and school social media sites for updates as we progress through this difficult time. We will remain in close communication with parents as this situation continues to evolve and will notify parents of any developments which impact our schools.

post_text:
Proud of our FAA Science Olympiad Team!!! Best of Luck this Saturday in Greenville!!!

Fred A. Anderson Elementary School is home to the ALL STAR Prodigies Science Olympiad team. The ALL STAR Prodigies are led by Coach Sheri Hale. Coach Hale won a Rural Participation Project scholarship in 2019 to attend the Science Olympiad coaches clinic. According to Sheri, "Having a Science Olympiad team has always been a dream of mine and this year the dream became a reality! I really enjoyed the coaches training in the fall and I came back with so much exciting tips, photos, and emails of other coaches willing to help the newbies!"
Our goal is to have a lot of fun together as a team. We’re really interested in the Team Spirit award! Since this is our very first Science Olympiad team for our school system, we’ve already achieved so much just by having a team! Sure, winning a medal would be great, but seeing how much the team has learned and seeing the excitement in their eyes makes them all winners in my book!

--Coach Sheri Hale

NC State Alumni Association
November 12, 2019 at 7:00 PM ·

As a teenager, Gayla Smith '76 had two options: work on her family's farm in Pamlico County or get in to college. For many, the second option can feel unattainable. As a first-generation college student, Gayla was able to take what she'd already learned in life and make it work for her future.
Meet other students who found a home at NC State: http://ncst.at/UBEVCU
📖 Fall 2019 - NC State magazine

shared_text:
Pamlico County High School Athletics - Hurricanes is at Smithfield-Selma High School.
September 28, 2019 at 7:01 PM · Smithfield, NC ·

The Hurricanes had a great showing at the Smithfield-Selma Invitational today!

The men finished fourth out of eleven entrants in the championship race, losing only to schools 3A or larger from the triangle area, in the process beating the host school and several other tough opponents.

The women finished third out of eight opponents in the championship race, with Cameron Lee leading the women and medaling.

In the open race, two Hurricanes medaled. Nyre Mattocks and Zayne Perkins had fantastic races and led the twelve Hurricane men who ran in the open.

The Hurricanes next race at home on Wednesday (10/2) versus the conference. The races begin at 4:00 pm at the high school track.

post_text: It’s a partial opening but thankful to have them under one roof again!!! Thanks for all the hours of hard work by so many to make this happen!!
shared_text:
Pamlico County Middle School
March 3, 2019 at 12:15 AM ·

YES!!!! You read that right!!!! PCMS faculty, staff and students are going back to the middle school!

Monday, March 4th will be our first day back on OUR campus since we were displaced in September by Hurricane Florence.

Here are a few reminders to make the transition as smooth as possible!

MORNING:

Student drop offs may begin at 7:30 in the back parking lot near the band room on McCotter Road (running beside the middle school)

6th Graders will report to the Family Learning Center
7th Graders will report to the cafeteria
8th Graders will report to the gym

AFTERNOON:

We dismiss at 3:15.

7th and 8th Grade Car Riders will be picked up in the same parking lot they were dropped off in the morning.

6th Grade Car Riders should be picked up in the first parking lot on McCotter Road (beside the middle school)

Looking forward to being all together once again!

post_text:
Hello everyone! This is Lisa Jackson, superintendent of Pamlico County Schools While Hurricane Florence was rough on Pamlico County...we can be thankful that it was not much worse. As most of you know, Pamlico County Middle School was flooded and those students will be moved to other campuses during clean up and restoration. 6th grade will be on the campus of Fred A. Anderson Elementary School....while 7th and 8th grade will be located at Pamlico County Primary School. Dr. Johnson will be sending a message out tomorrow with the details of how it will all work (to his students and families). We are so thankful to the other schools for being so willing to share their classrooms with us! We will resume classes this Thursday!! Friday will be a full day of school.
I am thankful to lead this amazing school district and I thank you for your patience as we begin our new normal at PCS. We look forward to seeing you all back on Thursday!

post_text:
Bus Transportation Registration for 2018-2019

If you will need bus transportation for your child for the new school year, registration for bus transportation is now underway. We have started the process of establishing our bus routes, and we ask that you register your child by Thursday, August 9.

You can go to our website at www.pamlicoschools.org and download the transportation form. Click on “Departments” and then the Transportation link. The completed form can be mailed or delivered to the Pamlico County Schools’ Transportation Dept. at 605 Anderson Drive, Bayboro, NC 28515, or it be can dropped off at your child’s school. Forms can be faxed as well to 252-745-3016. Forms are also available at each school, and please complete a separate form for each child.

Since buses have a limited seating capacity, you are encouraged to register your child as soon as possible, but no later than August 9. If seating is still available, forms received after August 9 will be processed in the order they are received. Please call the Transportation Department at 745-4601 if you have any questions.

Thank you to the PC Sheriff's Dept., Emergency personnel and the Pamlico County Schools personnel that jumped in to help out. Everyday we are charged with keeping our children safe. I am thankful that while this was a scary situation for all involved, all children and adults are home safe this afternoon. Thankful for blessings!

post_text: As many of you are aware, Pamlico County Schools was one of several schools that were included in a social media threat very early this morning. Upon notification of the threat, we were in contact with the Sheriff’s Department. The Sheriff’s Department believes this to be a hoax that has been passed around throughout many school districts in the state/country. We are thankful for the increased presence of the Sheriff’s Department in our schools. Always trust that the safety of our students is of the highest priority. The students are having a GREAT day in all four schools!

If you will need bus transportation for your child for the new school year, registration for bus transportation is now underway. We have started the process of establishing our bus routes, and we ask that you register your child by Thursday, August 10.

You can go to our website at www.pamlico.k12.nc.us and download the transportation form. Click on “Departments” and then the Transportation link. The completed form can be mailed or delivered to the Pamlico County Schools’ Transportation Dept. at 605 Anderson Drive, Bayboro, NC 28515, or it be can dropped off at your child’s school. Forms are also available at each school, and please complete a separate form for each child.

Since buses have a limited seating capacity, you are encouraged to register your child as soon as possible, but no later than August 10. If seating is still available, forms received after August 10 will be processed in the order they are received. Please call the Transportation Department at 745-4601 if you have any questions.
